These facilities shall be located subject to the following considerations:
The availability of suitable facilities outside this State for the disposal of low-level nuclear waste produced in this State;
That there are proper safeguards to the health and safety of the public and the quality of the environment;
That facilities are available at reasonable cost commensurate with adequate protection of public health and safety, and of the environment;
That there is due consideration of social values and of the reasonable and beneficial use of land and natural resources;
That there is due consideration for industry and commerce, the revenues, and development of the State and its political subdivisions, and the employment and welfare of the people;
That there is due consideration of alternatives over burial or other land disposal of hazardous or low-level nuclear waste, such as source reduction, reuse, resource recovery, and incineration;
That there is due consideration for the expeditious ultimate disposal of hazardous waste in order to minimize reliance on interim storage;
That there is due consideration for managing sites following cessation of operations;
That there is due consideration for the equitable geographic distribution of sites, including:
Consideration of the feasibility of siting a facility within the same political subdivision from which the wastes principally originate;
Consideration of those subdivisions that presently have sites, to avoid to the extent feasible certifying sites disproportionately in any one subdivision;
That there is due consideration for local land use preference, as expressed in local planning and zoning provisions; and
That there is due consideration for the geological stability of a location and for the safety and preservation of public and private water supplies. If the location of a facility site will result in any adverse effects to a public or private water supply, the facility site may not be approved.
